As the measured extension increases the force on the spring increases, we are able to calculate the spring constant $k$by taking the slope of the graph obtained by plotting this data since $k$ is constant across the varied spring extensions. Equation of linear fit is at the top of the graph.

# Question 3

In the Hooke's law experiment we found $k = 59 \pm 2 \space (N/m)$
In the SHM experiment we found $k = 45 \pm 2 \space (N/m)$

$\Delta k = k_{hooke} - k_{SHM} = 59 - 45 = 14$
$\delta \Delta k = \sqrt{\delta k_{hooke}^2 + \delta k_{SHM}^2} = \sqrt{8} \approx 2.82842712$
$3\delta \Delta k = 8.48528136$
$3\delta \Delta k \leq \Delta k$
$\implies$ the numbers do not agree

# Question 4

Hooke's Law
	Advantage:  Simpler experiment, gives $k$ directly with no room for human timing error and less assumptions than SHM
	Disadvantage: Very sensitive to the fact that rubber bands don't actually follow Hooke's law, they degrade over time and at large extensions vary farther from an ideal spring
SHM
	Advantage: More variables to balance out the fact that the band is not an ideal spring, averaging time for oscillations gives much more accurate measurements
	Disadvantage: Human error in measuring the period is fairly high, especially with little weight as the amplitude was very small

Overall I think that the Hooke's law experiment was more accurate since it is significantly simpler to gather data for and introduces much less human error. I noticed during the SHM part that measuring the period was very difficult since it's hard to tell exactly when 1 period has happened and the fact that if you didn't give it enough energy to start the periods would end up very small at the end (which also shows that there is some external force acting to slow the oscillations down significantly which is also an issue).

# Question 5

The mass of the rubber band was measured to be $3.40 \pm 0.01 \space (g)$
The graphical analysis found the mass to be $1700 \pm 100 \space (g)$
$\Delta m = m_{graph} - m = 59 - 45 = 1696.6$
$\delta \Delta m = \sqrt{\delta m^2 + \delta m_{graph}^2} = 100.0000005$
$3\delta \Delta k = 300.0000015$
$3\delta \Delta k \leq \Delta k$
$\implies$ the numbers do not agree (obviously)


# Question 6

It does seem as if the band follows Hooke's law at shorter extensions given that both of the graphs are fairly linear however, I think it's pretty obvious that over larger extensions rubber bands do not follow Hooke's law. If you've ever played around with a rubber band you'd know that they deform and don't always go back to their original shape especially after being stretched very far or stretched many times in a row and that they get easier to stretch at longer extensions

# Question 7

For both experiments, more weights and more varied ranges of weight, i.e. much larger weights and much smaller weights (but probably more on the smaller side). Pre-stretch the bands so that they are worn out a little to prevent initial data points from being off. 

For Hooke's law maybe use a video recording to measure extension instead of ruler since holding it up next to the band introduces a lot of uncertainty. Allow the weights to settle in so that the rubber band fully stretches. 

For SHM Time more oscillations and probably use a video recording as well. Somehow account for damping, ideally the amplitude should stay constant in SHM but clearly it did not which I'm sure greatly affected the results
